  <subsection xml:id="subsec-AttributesVector">
    <title>The Attributes of Vectors</title>

    <p>
      When defining a vector, it is important to note its <term>magnitude</term> and the <term>direction</term>. 
    </p>

    <p>
      The <term>magnitude</term> of a vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is the distance from the tail to the tip (aka the length of the vector). 
      This is denoted as <m>\|\mathbf{v}\|</m>. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Given a vector <m>\mathbf{v} = \langle a,b \rangle</m>, we can determine its magnitude using the Pythagorean Theorem, as demonstrated in the figure below. 
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="sec121-fig-VectorMagnitudeR2">
      <caption>The Magnitude of the vectors <m>\mathbf{v}_0</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}</m></caption>
      <image source="sec121-VectorMagnitude-R2.png" width="50%">
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      By the Pythagorean Theorem, we have
      <md>
        <mrow> \|\mathbf{v}\| \amp= \sqrt{(a_1 - a_2)^2 + (b_1 - b_2)^2} </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= \sqrt{a^2 + b^2} </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The magnitude of a vector is really called the <term><m>\boldsymbol{\ell^2}</m> norm</term> or the <term>Euclidean norm</term> of a vector in more advanced math courses.
      In general, norms must satisfy the following three properties: 
      <ol marker="1.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\|\mathbf{v}\| \geq 0</m>, with <m>\|\mathbf{v}\| = 0</m> if and only if <m>\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\| \lambda\mathbf{v}\| = |\lambda|\|\mathbf{v}\|</m> for all scalars <m>\lambda \in \mathbb{R}</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\|\mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w}\| \leq \|\mathbf{v}\| + \|\mathbf{w}\|</m> for any two vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m>, with equallity only if <m>\mathbf{v} = 0</m>, <m>\mathbf{w} = 0</m>, or if <m>\mathbf{w} = \lambda\mathbf{v}</m> where <m>\lambda \geq 0</m>. 
            (This is the famous <term>triangle inequality</term>). 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      This isn't a linear algebra or functional analysis class, so we won't go deeper into norms here. 
      If you are interested, feel free to do more digging on your own (or ask Richard!). 
    </p>

    <p>
      Now let's discuss the <term>direction</term> of a vector. 
      The direction of a vector tells us where the vector is pointing. 
      We can indicate the direction of a vector by using the vector itself. 
      As you imagine, the magnitude of a vector has nothing to do with its direction, so we sometimes use a <term>unit vector</term>, which is a vector of length <m>1</m>, to indicate the direction, when it is not necessary to specify length. 
    </p>

    <p>
      If we have a unit vector whose tail is at the origin, then its tip lies on the unit circle. 
      We usually denote a unit vector by <m>\mathbf{e}</m>, defined as
      <md>
        \mathbf{e} = \langle \cos(\theta), \sin(\theta)\rangle
      </md>
      where <m>\theta</m> is the angle between <m>\mathbf{e}</m> and the positive <m>x</m>-axis, indicated in the figure below. 
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="sec121-fig-UnitVector-UnitCircle">
      <caption>The unit vector <m>\mathbf{e}</m> on the unit circle</caption>
      <image source="sec121-UnitVector-UnitCircle.png" width="50%">
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      But what if we are given an arbitrary non-zero vector and we want to find a unit vector in the same direction?
      One way to do so is to divide the vector by its magnitude (multiplying a positive scalar doesn't change the direction of a vector). 
      That is, given <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, the unit vector in the direction of <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is
      <md>
        \mathbf{e_v} = \frac{1}{\|\mathbf{v}\|}\mathbf{v}
      </md>
    </p>

    <proof>
      <title>A quick proof to show that <m>\mathbf{e_v}</m> is a unit vector</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>\mathbf{v}</m> be a non-zero vector. 
        Then <m>\|\mathbf{v}\| \gt 0</m>. 
        This implies that
        <md>
          <mrow>\|\mathbf{e_v}\| \amp= \left\|\frac{1}{\|\mathbf{v}\|}\mathbf{v}\right\| </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \left|\frac{1}{\|\mathbf{v}\|}\right| \|\mathbf{v}\| \amp\amp\text{by the second norm property} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \frac{1}{\|\mathbf{v}\|}\|\mathbf{v}\| \amp\amp\text{since } \frac{1}{\|\mathbf{v}\|} \gt 0 </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= 1 </mrow>
        </md>
        Hence, <m>\mathbf{e_v}</m> is a unit vector. 
      </p>
    </proof>
    
  </subsection>

